    <item>
      <title>daemon</title>
      <link>/braindump/posts/2025-08-05_17-34-29-daemon/</link>
      <pubDate>Tue, 05 Aug 2025 00:00:00 +0000</pubDate>
      <guid>/braindump/posts/2025-08-05_17-34-29-daemon/</guid>
      <description>&lt;h2 id=&#34;daemon&#34;&gt;Daemon&lt;/h2&gt;
&lt;p&gt;In computing, a daemon (also spelled demon) is a computer program that runs in the background, performing tasks without direct user interaction. It&amp;rsquo;s like a helpful assistant that quietly handles various system operations&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;h2 id=&#34;backlinks&#34;&gt;Backlinks&lt;/h2&gt;
&lt;ul&gt;
&lt;li&gt;&lt;a href=&#34;/braindump/posts/2025-08-05_17-32-51-rust_daemonize/&#34;&gt;rust daemonize&lt;/a&gt;&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ul&gt;</description>
    </item>
    <item>
      <title>alacritty</title>
      <link>/braindump/posts/2025-08-01_18-38-24-alacritty/</link>
      <pubDate>Fri, 01 Aug 2025 00:00:00 +0000</pubDate>
      <guid>/braindump/posts/2025-08-01_18-38-24-alacritty/</guid>
      <description>&lt;p&gt;Alacritty is a simple, GPU-accelerated terminal emulator written in &lt;a href=&#34;/braindump/posts/2025-07-29_00-38-11-rust/&#34;&gt;Rust&lt;/a&gt;. It supports scrollback, 24-bit colors, copy/paste, clicking on URLs, and custom key bindings.&lt;/p&gt;</description>
    </item>
    <item>
      <title>dmenu</title>
      <link>/braindump/posts/2025-08-01_18-33-27-dmenu/</link>
      <pubDate>Fri, 01 Aug 2025 00:00:00 +0000</pubDate>
      <guid>/braindump/posts/2025-08-01_18-33-27-dmenu/</guid>
      <description>&lt;p&gt;dmenu is a fast and lightweight dynamic menu for &lt;a href=&#34;/braindump/posts/20240220160349-xorg/&#34;&gt;X&lt;/a&gt;. It reads arbitrary text from stdin, and creates a menu with one item for each line. The user can then select an item, through the arrow keys or typing a part of the name, and the line is printed to stdout. dmenu_run is a wrapper that ships with the dmenu distribution that allows its use as an application launcher.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;h2 id=&#34;backlinks&#34;&gt;Backlinks&lt;/h2&gt;
&lt;ul&gt;
&lt;li&gt;&lt;a href=&#34;/braindump/posts/2025-08-01_18-29-20-rofi/&#34;&gt;rofi&lt;/a&gt;&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ul&gt;</description>
    </item>
    <item>
      <title>fd</title>
      <link>/braindump/posts/2025-08-01_19-27-26-fd/</link>
      <pubDate>Fri, 01 Aug 2025 00:00:00 +0000</pubDate>
      <guid>/braindump/posts/2025-08-01_19-27-26-fd/</guid>
      <description>&lt;p&gt;fd is a program written in &lt;a href=&#34;/braindump/posts/2025-07-29_00-38-11-rust/&#34;&gt;Rust&lt;/a&gt; to find entries in your filesystem. It is a simple, fast and user-friendly alternative to find. While it does not aim to support all of find&amp;rsquo;s powerful functionality, it provides sensible (opinionated) defaults for a majority of use cases.&lt;/p&gt;</description>
    </item>
